                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d726">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6902: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-03T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 3, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 3—1:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1061. Your 396, June 2, 7 p.m., was taken up this morning with the Chief of the
                    Far Eastern Division at the Foreign Office.<note n="65" xml:id="d726fn65">Jean
                        Chauvel.</note> He said that on May 24 the Foreign Office had transmitted to
                    the Ministry of Colonies the request of the Chinese Ambassador for facilities
                    for the transit of these tung oil shipments. Chauvel stated that he would at
                    once get in touch with the Minister of Colonies, explain the considerations set
                    out in your telegram and urge that for these reasons the Chinese Ambassador’s
                    request should be granted without delay.<note n="66" xml:id="d726fn66">The
                        Ambassador in France took up the question again on June 6.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
